\begin_layout Section
Context
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is one of my first titled Projects, a descendant of an especially old
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Life Management
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, somewhere before the strike of COVID-19.
 It is supposed to be kind of a to-do-list on steroids, just organizing
 all of the stuff I need to do, and originally my journal, as well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The base gist was a combination of a well-organized to-do-list, including
 scheduling and deadlining and sub-tasking without limit as I saw fit, and
 a journal that allowed more reflection; the journaling grew more complex
 as I tried to get more insight into my own life — at the cost of actual
 progress in it.
 I tried to expand mood tracking, that I did in the past, and tried to exactly
 time all of my actions; and then more activity, location, people, sleep,
 food, and so on.
 That ended quite quickly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As time progressed and I experimented with different forms of that, it coalesced
 mainly unto 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Progress Reports
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 — which detail Outline, Status, Results and Conclusions for each day, with
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Goals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\bar under
210602A:
\bar default
 Maintain a regular reporting habit which will detail Outline, Status, Results
 and Conclusions according to existing, acting and relevant projects, on
 a daily, weekly, monthly, seasonally and yearly time-scope.
 As part of that, maintain a continuous process of reflection and learning,
 and maintain a personal history,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\bar under
210602B:
\bar default
 Maintain Project statements to detail main purposes (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Mesa Objectives
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), and their Outline, Status, Results and Conclusions — including a task
 and issue board, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210615A
\bar default
 Themes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each season — Autumn, Winter, Spring, Summer, pick a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Theme
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for progress.
 A theme (as inspired by 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "several episodes of the Cortex podcast"
target "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2zugiZ73SyM"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "videos of the YouTube channel CGPGrey"
target "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NVGuFdX5guE"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the 
\shape slanted

\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "TheMe System Journal"
target "https://www.themesystem.com/"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\shape default
Product), is a broad, directional and resonant word that embodies a rough
 area I would like to invest in.
 Examples include Health, Clarity, Less, Foundations, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Broad
\series default
 — meaning there is a plethora of ways to invest in the area, that can be
 very different from each other — health can be mental or physical.
 Physical health can be about diet, sleep, hygiene or exercise, each of
 which a subject that could be tackled in many, many different ways by itself.
 Broadness insures that the subject remains fitting and workable even as
 reality changes drastically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Directional
\series default
 — meaning that it genuinely can direct me to different projects and goals,
 and make judgment between decisions.
 A Spring of Success, for example, would generally be 
\shape slanted
too
\shape default
 broad; it is somewhat inconcrete, and does not say anything about how to
 achieve that success.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Resonant
\series default
 — meaning that it genuinely resonates with me, I genuinely desire to improve
 in the subject, and I feel an at least rough understanding of how to approach
 it 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Themes can work on the current state — for example 
\shape slanted
Health
\shape default
 and 
\shape slanted
Family
\shape default
 are both valid themes with very concrete goals; They can also be more vague
 — I used 
\shape slanted
Standing Up
\shape default
, just as a general idea of getting out of bad habits and people and unproductiv
ity, without specifics in mind.
 They can also work on form: 
\shape slanted
Clarity
\shape default
 deals with how we approach things and how we make decisions.
 
\shape slanted
Less
\shape default
 is a fairly meta theme, about taking 
\shape slanted
less
\shape default
 goals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike most other orientation objects, theme do not delineate a precise
 goal state.
 Even with the more concrete Health and Family, the idea is never to get
 some Specific, Measurable, Attainable or even Time-Bound goal.
 There is no need to be nervous about reaching some specific things.
 The idea is 
\shape slanted
improvement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210606A
\bar default
 Aspects 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, I assign everything I need to talk about a color, called an
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

aspect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which roughly corresponds with a base motivation (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

axiom
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) as delineated by 
\emph on
Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs
\emph default
 (see appendix-A).
 Specifically:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color red
Red 
\color inherit
corresponds with physiological needs — health, food, sleep, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color pink
Pink
\color inherit
 corresponds with sexual needs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color purple
Purple 
\color inherit
corresponds with psychological needs — love, belongingness and esteem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color green
Green
\color inherit
 corresponds with self-actualization needs, specifically through learning,
 applying skill and self-expression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color gray
Gray 
\color inherit
corresponds to the safety need — trying to control the existing environment
 to ease stability and day to day work, and making maintenance work to repair
 any problems that arise in it
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color blue
Blue
\color inherit
 corresponds to the need to do good in the world — to make the lives of
 others better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aspect blue does not correspond to a motivation on Maslow's hierarchy,
 but in my view is indeed an axiomatic need.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally, this system delineates an additional 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

meta
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 aspect:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color lightgray
Steel
\color inherit
 corresponds to the need to fulfill the base needs mentioned above; it should
 deal with decision making itself and the integration of the above stated
 needs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In previous iterations of this project, instrumental aspects (which referred
 to significant mesa objectives) were created; see appendix-B for more details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By categorizing objects with this system, I am able to more clearly integrate
 between my needs, and see which one I have more or less issues with at
 the moment; it also allows me to remember the higher purpose behind things,
 and thus to be able to better determine the path I should be taking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210606B
\bar default
 Projects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I can optionally farther specify any object with a Project.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A project is defined by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A mesa objective — that is, a goal I set in order to advance one of the
 higher, base motivations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Systems set to achieve that mesa objective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The state of said systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Systems
\emph default
 then, denote a fabric of rules and plans to practice, which will progress
 the project up to its goal, and maintain it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sum of all the systems of all projects essentially implies my to-do-list;
 unlike the base motives or the mesa-objectives, which detail only desirable
 
\shape slanted
states
\shape default
, the 
\emph on
system
\emph default
 defines a 
\shape slanted
course of action
\shape default
.
 Looking at all project in their corresponding aspects, and the actions
 I need to take to engage with said systems, I should be able to look more
 easily through the timeline, and make sure I can achieve my mesa goals
 in a timely manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a general rule, each project should have a project directory (to be specified
 in a future gray project) and a statement as detailed in 
\shape slanted
System210606C
\shape default
.
 Some projects are created mostly for completion and don't require such
 order and method.
 These are the detailed in this document, in 
\shape slanted
Appendix-C
\shape default
.
 This is mostly meant for relationship projects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I stylize project with one-word, UPPER_CASE names.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210610A
\bar default
 Identifiers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to be able to search refer to objects (goals, tasks, decisions,
 etc.) in a convenient manner, while still allowing for renaming/non-naming,
 I will assign each an identifier string in the following manner, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

{TYPE}{DATE}{NUM}{SUB_NUMS}
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
TYPE refers to the object class (system, decision, goal, etc.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
DATE is the object creation date, formatted 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yymmdd
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NUM is a letter enumerating the objects of that type that were created that
 day, prior: — for example for the third decision made in the same day,
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

C
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If creating identifier for a sub-item, SUB_NUMS will be dash - delimited
 list of numbers indicating the sub-item number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, presume this is written in the system sub-item 
\shape slanted
Identifiers
\shape default
, the first sub-item of the system Statements, which was the third system
 for the project created on 2021-06-06.
 Therefore, it gets the identifier 
\shape slanted
System
\shape default
210606C-1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If referring to an object outside the current project scope, add 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

{PROJECT}/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 prefix — e.g 
\shape slanted
CONTROL/System
\shape default
210606C-1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

{PROJECT}/
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

{NAME}
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should be 
\shape slanted
slanted
\shape default
 when using to refer an object.
 All of the ID should be 
\bar under
underlined
\bar default
 when declared.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main idea is that I can now refer to other objects (for example, say,
 in a project statement as detailed in 
\shape slanted
System
\shape default
210606C-2, independent of possible title changes (or lack of title), and
 independent of changes in order (for example 4.3.1, the titling index of
 this sub-item, is not necessarily consistent).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210606D
\bar default
 Proposals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This system is supposed to formalize my decision making process, and does
 so very simply:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An idea I have that I'm thinking about implementing is called a proposal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An Open Proposal is a proposal that I am currently thinking about.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Closed Proposal is a proposal that I have decided either to implement
 in some form or reject.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Decision is a proposal scheduled to be implemented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main idea is to be used in integration with 
\shape slanted
System210606C
\shape default
, to be written down.
 To prevent ideas from floating around aimlessly until fading, and to empower
 the act of decision by writing down the thought.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210606C
\bar default
 Statements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Statements are documents which detail projects and progress — as said, the
 goals, plan, and state, as well as the history of those.
 The idea being that it will allow me to organize what I need and wish to
 do and the circumstances surrounding these tasks, and allow me to learn
 and improve both in general and in the stated project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\bar under
210606C-1
\bar default
 Project Statements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every project will have a statement, delineating its goal, systems, and
 status, as well as reflections upon it to optimize its process.
 Similar statements will be created for various time scopes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A directory named 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Statements
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should be created in the project directory.
 For each project defined, it should have a NAME.lyx file, which outlines
 the Project in the following tree-like manner:
\end_layout

