\begin_layout Section
Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs can be quickly defined with the following two
 graphs; each lists the basic needs/motivations people tend to have, and
 delineate the sequence in which they tend to come in.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/atai/Projects/ARCHIVES/Versions/03-210602/Code-Steel (ORG)/LAWBOOK/Axioms/.visuals/Happiness, Maslow Pyramid.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
Figure 1: Pyramid form of the hierarchy; each need dominates motivation
 after the one below it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/atai/Projects/ARCHIVES/Versions/03-210602/Code-Steel (ORG)/LAWBOOK/Axioms/.visuals/Happiness, Dynamic Hierarchy.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
Figure 2: Dynamic form.
 The strength of each change is dynamic, and it's simply the top one that
 takes priority, where the needs are usually fulfilled in the typical sequence.
\end_layout

